John,

You asked about the tax angle on a 5-year versus a 3-year renewal. Quick thoughts.

5-year (locked-in):
- Tenant improvements get straight-line over the lesser of useful life or lease term. A 5-year lease means a 5-year useful-life cap on TI depreciation.
- The $20K renovation credit from Lakeside, if structured as a Tenant Improvement Allowance, gets amortized over 5 years (=$4K/yr deduction) net of section 110 reduction.
- Tighter than 3-year means less optionality. If a fourth shop opens nearby in 2028, you can't pivot without breaking lease.

3-year (with renewal option):
- Same TI useful-life cap, but on a 3-year horizon (=higher per-year deduction = $6.7K/yr on the $20K renovation credit).
- More optionality if shop landscape changes (acquisition, fourth shop, downsizing).
- Risk: rent reset at year 3 is unknown. Could be worse than the +12% Brennan is proposing now.

My read on your situation:
- The Market Street bay is your highest-revenue location (Hector's data: ~$880K/yr gross).
- It's also the office. Moving costs you 3 weeks minimum and $25-40K in relocation.
- The shop equipment is largely permanent installations. Lift posts, paint booth ductwork - hard to migrate.
- Replacement comparable space in the corridor is at $19/sqft (per Tony's pulls).

My recommendation:
- Push for 5-year on terms BETTER than +12% Year 1. Your real walk-away should be anything that prices the bay above the corridor at $19.20/sqft (= $123K/yr or $122,880).
- Brennan's +12% offer brings you to $19.04/sqft. That's roughly at corridor. Anchor your counter at +6% (= $17.96/sqft = within corridor) on a 5-year with renovation credit and personal-guarantee cap held at $250K (no movement on the cap).
- The personal guarantee reduction from uncapped to $250K is actually a real concession. Don't ignore it.

